06208nam a22011175i 9780691211138DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212021nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2020949577  a97806912111387 a10.1515/97806912111382doi  a(DE-B1597)573240  a(OCoLC)1253313281  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aBJ1533.C7bS76 2021 7aPHI0050002bisacsh04a170/.442231 aStorey, Benjamin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWhy We Are Restless :bOn the Modern Quest for Contentment /cBenjamin Storey, Jenna Silber Storey. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2021  a1 online resource (264 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNew Forum Books ;v6900tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPrologue We Restless Souls -- tIntroduction Four French Thinkers on the Modern Quest for Contentment -- tChapter 1 Montaigne: The Art of Ordinary Life -- tChapter 2 Pascal: The Inhumanity of Immanence -- tChapter 3 Rousseau: The Tragedy of Nature's Redeemer -- tChapter 4 Tocqueville: Democracy and the Naked Soul -- tConclusion Liberal Education and the Art of Choosing -- tAcknowledgments -- tSuggested Readings -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA beautifully written exploration of how the way we pursue happiness makes us unhappyWe live in an age of unprecedented prosperity, yet everywhere we see signs that our pursuit of happiness has proven fruitless. Dissatisfied, we seek change for the sake of change-even if it means undermining the foundations of our common life. In Why We Are Restless, Benjamin and Jenna Storey offer a profound and beautiful reflection on the roots of this malaise and examine how we might begin to cure ourselves.Drawing on the insights of Montaigne, Pascal, Rousseau, and Tocqueville, Why We Are Restless explores the modern vision of happiness that leads us on, and the disquiet that follows it like a lengthening shadow. In the sixteenth century, Montaigne articulated an original vision of human life that inspired people to see themselves as individuals dedicated to seeking contentment in the here and now, but Pascal argued that that we cannot find happiness through pleasant self-seeking, only anguished God-seeking. Rousseau later tried and failed to rescue Montaigne's worldliness from Pascal's attack. Steeped in these debates, Tocqueville visited the United States in 1831 and, observing a people "restless in the midst of their well-being," discovered what happens when an entire nation seeks worldly contentment-and finds mostly discontent.Arguing that the philosophy we have inherited, despite pretending to let us live as we please, produces remarkably homogenous and unhappy lives, Why We Are Restless makes the case that finding true contentment requires rethinking our most basic assumptions about happiness.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aContentment. 0aHappiness. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh  aChristianity.  aDemocracy in America.  aFrench philosophy.  aanxiety.  aatheism.  aclassical education.  adecadence.  ademocracy.  adepression.  aelites.  agood life.  ahistory of philosophy.  ahyperactivity.  aideal of happiness.  aimmanent contentment.  aliberal education.  amaterialism.  ameaning of life.  amodernity.  amoralist.  aparadox of choice.  apolitical philosophy.  apurpose of life.  apursuit of happiness.  aroots of modernity.  aself.  askepticism.  aunhappiness.  awhat is happiness.1 aStorey, Jenna Silber, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz9